00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:48.980
brewery in the country when we opened in Rehoboth
Beach Delaware. I know there's a number of

00:02:48.980 --> 00:02:54.579
home brewers in this community and I was basically
just brewing beer on glorified home brew equipment.

00:02:54.579 --> 00:03:02.422
I had an early three keg brewing system that
we did some things to to make it more, you

00:03:02.422 --> 00:03:05.450
know, volume friendly. But right from the
get go when there was all the first, the first

00:03:05.450 --> 00:03:11.950
sort of, uh, generation of craft brewers,
some awesome ones, and they were brewing really

00:03:11.950 --> 00:03:16.280
flavorful, intensely flavorful beer in comparison
to largest breweries selling in this country

00:03:16.280 --> 00:03:20.860
which intentionally made their beer more approachable,
some would say dumbed down, uh, but very,

00:03:20.860 --> 00:03:25.189
very consistent but very samey. Frankly, most
of the largest breweries that sell beer in

00:03:25.189 --> 00:03:31.819
this country make some slight variation of
the same style of light lager. And the first

00:03:31.819 --> 00:03:38.830
generation of craft brewers came in and kind
of re embraced continental styles like Pale

00:03:38.830 --> 00:03:42.879
Ales from England or Lagers from Germany.
So knowing we were starting small, we said

00:03:42.879 --> 00:03:48.299
we're gonna do something very different, we're
gonna try and embrace the entire culinary

00:03:48.299 --> 00:03:53.849
landscape for potential ingredients to brew
with and that's where that sort of motto of

00:03:53.849 --> 00:03:59.349
'off centered ales for off centered people'
came from, was that philosophy of that kind

00:03:59.349 --> 00:04:05.890
of global approach to ingredients for brewing.
If you look back in the longest history of

00:04:05.890 --> 00:04:10.260
beer, the beer geeks in this room know the
Reinheitsgebot, the beer purity act of 1516.

00:04:10.260 --> 00:04:13.230
Bavarian government mandated beer could only
be made with water, barley and hops. Yeast

00:04:13.230 --> 00:04:15.569
wasn't included cause it wasn't discovered
by Louis Pasteur in its context of how it

00:04:15.569 --> 00:04:20.190
works in beer yet. And 90 something percent
of the beer sold globally, today, commercially

00:04:20.190 --> 00:04:25.540
roughly is kind of done in accordance with
that Reinheitsgebot. I say roughly cause the

00:04:25.540 --> 00:04:32.230
biggest breweries use a lot of corn and rice,
cheaper adjuncts that, uh, instead of all

00:04:32.230 --> 00:04:39.100
barley. But if you look back in the longer
history of beer, 1516, we've, human beings

00:04:39.100 --> 00:04:46.800
have been drinking beer for about 9,000 years.
The first known, like by physical evidence,

00:04:46.800 --> 00:04:51.930
fermented cereal based beverage, i.e. a beer,
was discovered in the Jiahu dig site in China.

00:04:51.930 --> 00:04:55.100
We do that beer in collaboration with the
molecular archaeologists that vetted that

00:04:55.100 --> 00:05:00.000
discovery called Chateau Jiahu and it's made
with Sake yeast, Sake rice, Hawthorne fruits,

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:07.319
so that is the longest history of brewing.
So this concept of beer really only being

00:05:07.319 --> 00:05:16.680
four ingredients has only been with us about,
for, for ten percent of our human brewing

00:05:16.680 --> 00:05:24.350
timeline in the history of civilization. Yet,
the recent generations just kind of assume

00:05:24.350 --> 00:05:29.330
that beer is beer. That kind of happened until
the craft brewing renaissance in this country.

00:05:29.330 --> 00:05:35.990
The Europeans were a little bit better than
we were at preserving these traditions of

00:05:35.990 --> 00:05:40.360
brewing very inspired, very flavorful beers
that were outside the light Lager, Juggernaut

00:05:40.360 --> 00:05:44.730
style that dominates globally, but still they
were existing styles. And you look at these

00:05:44.730 --> 00:05:50.729
cultures, almost every culture around the
world had its own indigenous beers and, of

00:05:50.729 --> 00:05:58.060
course, they predated the Reinheitsgebot so
they too kind of just embraced this idea of

00:05:58.060 --> 00:06:03.449
whatever could grow in their region or their
world, whatever they could pick out of their

00:06:03.449 --> 00:06:08.629
terroir or their local ground, that's what
they made beer with. A project we did, I don't

00:06:08.629 --> 00:06:13.289
know, probably now it's been, my son's 13,
it's been 9-10 years ago, was when the first

00:06:13.289 --> 00:06:17.680
shock and awe bombing was happening and I
was watching a dinosaur video with my son

00:06:17.680 --> 00:06:22.729
to stop watching CNN and the other stuff that
was dominating TV and there was, they showed

00:06:22.729 --> 00:06:27.110
a picture of dinosaurs and da,da,da,da, before
continental drift there was the one super

00:06:27.110 --> 00:06:38.550
continent and that gave us the inspiration
to do a beer called Pangaea. I was stuck in

00:06:38.550 --> 00:06:42.729
this pretty remote little area in Montana
where we were on vacation with our family

00:06:42.729 --> 00:06:54.590
and it wasn't like I could go, do too much
outside of ski and hang with my family. But

00:06:54.590 --> 00:07:04.740
really once I watched that I put my son to
bed and for the next three or four hours I

00:07:04.740 --> 00:07:12.970
sat there using Google as a resource and I
decided, you know, I wanna do a beer with

00:07:12.970 --> 00:07:16.240
every continent included as an ingredient.
Kind of our way as putting the fractured world,

00:07:16.240 --> 00:07:22.990
that shock and awe bombing, messy world that
we live in, back into one thing, you know,

00:07:22.990 --> 00:07:29.700
a sort of cohesive thing. I did that without
knowing that Antarctica was a continent, I

00:07:29.700 --> 00:07:31.380
wasn't geography major.
[Laughter]

00:07:31.380 --> 00:07:36.940
&gt;&gt;Sam Calagione: I was an English major, not
geography major. So that presented some challenges

00:07:36.940 --> 00:07:41.970
as I did my Google searches for what we could
include. Every other continent was fairly

00:07:41.970 --> 00:07:46.699
easy but literally within four or five hours,
that evening, sippin' beers and looking out

00:07:46.699 --> 00:07:52.560
at the snow, we came up with this recipe and
by the next morning I had emails back from,

00:07:52.560 --> 00:07:55.710
you know, I had penguin shit or water to choose
from in Antarctica.

00:07:55.710 --> 00:07:59.460
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Sam Calagione: You'd be surprised which

00:07:59.460 --> 00:08:01.599
one we chose.
[Laughter]

00:08:01.599 --> 00:08:08.030
&gt;&gt;Sam Calagione: But that night, searching
those ingredients, that was obviously the

00:08:08.030 --> 00:08:11.851
real challenge. And through that search I
found a US military base down there and as

00:08:11.851 --> 00:08:17.740
I went further into their website world, I
found like a 'contact me' type thing and by

00:08:17.740 --> 00:08:23.689
the next morning there was a "Hell yeah! We're
all home brewers down here cause we can't

00:08:23.689 --> 00:08:24.789
get beer."
[Laughter]

