00:09:01.420 --> 00:09:05.040
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Sam Calagione: So we get the four, five

00:09:05.040 --> 00:09:09.050
gallon buckets every year of the Antarctic
water and it has crystallized ginger from

00:09:09.050 --> 00:09:15.350
Australia and all these different ingredients.
And I, I've gotten to be friendly with Adam

00:09:15.350 --> 00:09:22.190
through the years and got invited to speak
here again a few years ago and for small businesses,

00:09:22.190 --> 00:09:27.290
the idea for this Urkontinent which is kind
of a word that I think has more Germanic history

00:09:27.290 --> 00:09:34.120
and uses but it essentially also means Pangaea,
is I think an earlier word that predates it

00:09:34.120 --> 00:09:39.750
for what this super continent was called.
When Adam approached me about seeing if we

00:09:39.750 --> 00:09:45.990
had an opportunity to collaborate here, I
thought the best way into this, because the

00:09:45.990 --> 00:09:51.601
moment that we're at in the brewing history
of America, we now have more breweries in

00:09:51.601 --> 00:09:55.779
America than we had pre prohibition, back
when every neighborhood had its own brewery

00:09:55.779 --> 00:10:02.770
and it's impressive. In the year 2012 there's
now over 2,012 breweries in the country, average

00:10:02.770 --> 00:10:13.820
American lives within 10 miles of a brewery,
amazing stats. But what's more incredible

00:10:13.820 --> 00:10:19.089
is we're on the cusp of this, another giant
surge of brewery openings. So many of us,

00:10:19.089 --> 00:10:26.649
I'd say 98 percent of those of us that opened
those 2,000 breweries, started as home brewers

00:10:26.649 --> 00:10:34.410
and just turned our passion into our livelihood.
While there's 2,000 breweries open right now

00:10:34.410 --> 00:10:43.290
there's also 800 people that are registered
in the startup phase of opening a brewery.

00:10:43.290 --> 00:10:54.050
So here we are as craft brewers with about
six or seven percent market share and we're

00:10:54.050 --> 00:11:01.290
getting ready to have about 800 breweries
open. But instead of freaking out and the

00:11:01.290 --> 00:11:11.620
biggest craft breweries being like, "Oh, we
gotta do what we can to stop them." We kind

00:11:11.620 --> 00:11:18.720
of all came together as a community and do
what we can to help them open whether it's

00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:23.300
through our work as an association called
the Brewer's Association that represents a

00:11:23.300 --> 00:11:30.290
vast majority of small breweries in this country
or individually when a brewery like ours that

00:11:30.290 --> 00:11:35.079
might be mid-sized reaches out to make a beer
with a brewery like Shorts in Michigan or

00:11:35.079 --> 00:11:39.649
the Brewery in L.A. that are maybe, you know,
less than one tenth of our size, even though

00:11:39.649 --> 00:11:44.839
Dogfish is only one fifteenth of one percent
domestic market share, we are sizable and

00:11:44.839 --> 00:11:51.540
established now that we can use our outreach
and our resources to engage with these smaller

00:11:51.540 --> 00:11:57.589
breweries. And we learn as much as they do
when we do these projects. But knowing we're,

00:11:57.589 --> 00:12:02.211
at this moment, sort of a reflection point
of an explosion of good beer, I thought it

00:12:02.211 --> 00:12:07.490
could be really fun if we could do this project
together in a way that lets us celebrate and

00:12:07.490 --> 00:12:14.010
do a sort of tutorial without it feeling teachey
or preachy on the ways that small companies

00:12:14.010 --> 00:12:18.720
can use, not just Google, but technology that
is accessible to grow because Dogfish, whether

00:12:18.720 --> 00:12:26.130
it was the Pangaea project or today, we don't
have focus groups, we don't have rooms full

00:12:26.130 --> 00:12:35.380
of MBAs, when we decide to do a project we
just decide to do it ourselves and often times

00:12:35.380 --> 00:12:45.130
that involves a lot of online research. And
much like the internet in general has been

00:12:45.130 --> 00:12:59.329
a great leveler on the marketing side of beer;
a brewery like Dogfish Head can have a social

00:12:59.329 --> 00:13:07.139
media world that's nearly as robust as the
largest breweries. We're like, I don't know,

00:13:07.139 --> 00:13:10.709
the 20 something biggest brewery in the country
but my wife, Mariah, who runs all our social

00:13:10.709 --> 00:13:18.480
media has done such a great job at that world
that we have the presence of, I think, like

00:13:18.480 --> 00:13:27.410
the fourth or fifth biggest American brewery
online whether it be gauge it by Facebook

00:13:27.410 --> 00:13:35.040
and Twitter or whatever she's doing that day.
But the important thing is we recognize an

00:13:35.040 --> 00:13:40.920
obligation to share with the other small breweries
that are just coming online or are smaller

00:13:40.920 --> 00:13:45.459
than us now, the ways you can be successful
in business. And it's, again, not preachy

00:13:45.459 --> 00:13:49.130
because there's as many different approaches
to opening and starting and brewing beer as

00:13:49.130 --> 00:13:54.600
there is great styles of beer that are out
there. Beer is a subjective thing, we all

00:13:54.600 --> 00:13:57.320
have different palates, so there should be
a limitless, you know, landscape of different

00:13:57.320 --> 00:14:03.540
beers that are out there. But what is important
is, you know, like I said, collectively all

00:14:03.540 --> 00:14:08.889
the small breweries are seven percent market
share so we really need to stick together

00:14:08.889 --> 00:14:15.829
and a kind of rising tide floats all ships
as it gets more competitive in the beer market.

00:14:15.829 --> 00:14:22.040
You know, a few weeks ago, Anheuser Busch
InBev reached out to purchase Modelo, it's

00:14:22.040 --> 00:14:29.089
still sort of pending a Department of Justice
look at it, but for all intents and purposes,

00:14:29.089 --> 00:14:33.960
that most likely will happen. So they'll go
from having roughly a 47 percent market share

00:14:33.960 --> 00:14:39.940
to 53, you know, overnight with one purchase.
That's six percent which is about the entire

00:14:39.940 --> 00:14:46.139
world of craft beer, all 2,000 of us, but
that moment and that much market share shifted

00:14:46.139 --> 00:14:51.970
in the time it took for those two companies
to sign contracts to merge. So, God bless

00:14:51.970 --> 00:14:56.920
em', it's a, there's competitive components
that I'm not gonna go into here, other than

00:14:56.920 --> 00:15:03.570
to say our priority as small breweries, is
helping the other small breweries grow so

00:15:03.570 --> 00:15:12.860
that small breweries can still exist. So,
that's my little preaching here about what

00:15:12.860 --> 00:15:18.650
we wanted to do with this project. So then
moving into the project itself, basically

00:15:18.650 --> 00:15:25.139
we try to make this as iterative and open
as possible. And while the Pangaea project

00:15:25.139 --> 00:15:37.830
was so much fun to do, that was just me in
one room, sitting there for four nights doing

00:15:37.830 --> 00:15:46.319
Google searches of ingredients that led to
that beer and that recipe. This one, instead

00:15:46.319 --> 00:15:52.540
of a bunch of beer geeks from the Google and
Dogfish side just sitting down saying, "I

00:15:52.540 --> 00:15:59.480
like this. I like that," we said why don't
we try and make not just, the reference point

00:15:59.480 --> 00:16:04.550
of Urkontinent is obviously a global reference
point, let's make the actual conceptionalization

00:16:04.550 --> 00:16:10.819
of the beer as global as possible. So what
I'll do is since it's hard for me to talk

00:16:10.819 --> 00:16:17.269
in the actual, um, what products we used or
what kind of tools we used to do that, let

00:16:17.269 --> 00:16:24.639
me just get that list out of the way and then
I can go back to speaking the way I do. A

00:16:24.639 --> 00:16:31.360
guy from our team, Trey, runs our IT department
and he was instrumental on our side in helping

00:16:31.360 --> 00:16:35.839
these things happen because I don't often
speak the same language as my friends from

00:16:35.839 --> 00:16:41.050
Google that were on this project. So really
just moving through these, these, the products

00:16:41.050 --> 00:16:48.060
that we used, we used, and these guys can
go further into how we used them as we do

00:16:48.060 --> 00:16:50.970
this, we used Google search, obviously, for
ingredient research and searching the whole

00:16:50.970 --> 00:16:56.940
way, we used Google Docs for the online spreadsheets,
documentation about the project, we used Moderator

00:16:56.940 --> 00:17:02.110
for the initial idea submissions which I think
is just a really cool component of this that

00:17:02.110 --> 00:17:06.870
I don't thinks been done in the beer world
before, and also for the voting and comments.

00:17:06.870 --> 00:17:12.190
The fact that you don't even, you can submit
something or not but you can also just click

00:17:12.190 --> 00:17:17.810
on, if you like someone else's suggestion
and that way it just became this really democratic

00:17:17.810 --> 00:17:24.010
view of the ingredients and the process. We
used Google chat as we went through this process,

00:17:24.010 --> 00:17:31.670
we would meet up every month or so as we were
bringing this toward the test batch and then

00:17:31.670 --> 00:17:37.190
from the test batch toward the market place.
We did Google Sites for the actual Urkontinent

00:17:37.190 --> 00:17:43.080
website and we used Google Video, some people
submitted videos to go along with their ingredient

00:17:43.080 --> 00:17:52.020
submissions. We also set up our Google+ business
page, my wife did, at some point during that

00:17:52.020 --> 00:17:53.640
process and that's another important social
media tool that we use. So what was really

00:17:53.640 --> 00:17:59.760
neat about this global component is you had
this influx of over 100, I think, ingredient

00:17:59.760 --> 00:18:08.560
ideas, that came into our world, so you had
the one component of how many people in the

00:18:08.560 --> 00:18:14.510
Google universe would have liked to see that
